<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
First, thanks to all of you who took the time to read and consider what I had to say.  It shows in your replies, and I really appreciate that.  (I'm a little confused by some of the posts about corny corn, but... um... sure it means something to you guys  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">)<P>I'm not a newbie in Norrath, nor on Povar.  I've been an EQ player for nearly 2 years now, and Povar is my original server.  I've played on 6 different servers, and yes, Povar is much better than others.  I've lived life as both guilded and unguilded, small guild vs. uberguild - chose the small guild because I like the atmosphere much better.  Hands of Faith became a member of the Povar Alliance of Small Guilds in order to ensure its members the opportunity to raid on a larger scale, without having to leave HoF.  This may not be how you would choose to do things, but it works pretty well for us most of the time.  None of us in HoF subscribe to the idea that one has to join a huge guild in order to be able to go on certain raids - we've seen in action that large multiguild raids can and do work, and work well.  Differently, to be sure  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> but done right, they are fun and rewarding.<P>A couple of facts to address some of your comments:  First, Eronmore did advise several of the Triton who showed up in Feerrott that Friday - we were half an hour from going up, and so folks were in the process of arriving.  We had two break groups in Feerrott, though yes, they were not yet at the portal because they were waiting for the remainder of the folks intending to break, and it's easier to go through the spec caves en masse.  Now, you may not agree with any of that approach, but that's how things were organized.<P>Second: this was not a pick-up raid.  This was a raid that had been planned for about 3 weeks.  We knew about the patch on the Tuesday, so we assumed two things: one, Fear was "taken" on Wednesday post-patch, and two, there would likely be a post-patch patch  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> which would probably mean Fear was taken again on Thursday.  Therefore, we planned for Friday afternoon.<P>So.  I fail to see where we somehow should have known, prior to the emergency patch on Thursday night/Friday morning, that Triton would have been going up to Fear.  And I don't see how we should have planned our raid better.  We planned it as well as we could have, given all we knew at the time.  It's rather a specious argument that you only go up once every 7 days and we should have just planned around Triton, and that Triton wasn't/isn't the problem.  Your raiding party showed up after the Alliance group was in zone on a day when, up til about 10 hours before, we really had no reason to believe Triton or RA would be in Fear.<P>Again - this was NOT a pickup raid, it was a full Alliance raid involving several guilds.  I don't see how much more we could have done on the planning side to avoid the conflict.<P>I also don't see how much earlier than a raid start time we would need to have our groups gather in order to have been considered "viable" by your terms. Half an hour is not enough, so... 1 hour? 2 hours? 5?  A Day?  Most of the people on the raid were coming home from work or finishing dinner, and were already camped in Feerrott.  Short of camping the portal itself, or camping in Fear... what more do we do to convince you we're serious?<P>Was it too much to ask that Triton make an effort to cooperate with the raid group?  The point's been made that Triton has done so with other guild raids, and happily.  Fine and dandy, glad to hear it, but... it didn't happen in this case.  Why not?  And more to the point, what are we, i.e. Triton and the other guilds of Povar, going to do about that?<P>I wasn't privy to the conversation Eronmore had with any of the Triton, but when I discussed it with Krohn later, he said no one had passed that info on to him.  Since we don't know who failed to pass what on to whom, there's no real way to deal with that.  Obviously, whoever Eronmore spoke with didn't take what he said seriously, didn't take the Alliance raid seriously, and didn't feel any obligation to be decent and at least advise your raid leader that there was another raid group present and planning to go up.<P>(On a personal note, as a GL myself on Povar, and as an officer in my guild on another server, I can assure you, if I heard that something like this happened with my guildmembers, I would be down on everyone's asses who attended the raid until I found out why the raid leader wasn't told, and who it was that failed to pass on that information.  They would most likely get reamed and if it happened ever again, they'd be flat out of the  guild.  But those are our standards *shrug*.)<P>As for PnP - me, personally, I can deal with anyone pulling it on me, because I try to work out a fair means of sharing spawns.  I've done it all of my time in Norrath, and I will continue doing it.  And yes, even on the long camp spawns, even though that's a bitch kitty.  I remember that I'm one of 2000+ citizens of Norrath on Povar and that my having fun should never be had at the expense of others doing so.<P>By definition, if Triton and the other major guilds on Povar are unwilling to go along with any kind of scheduling (though, btw, that's exactly what you are doing with RA on CT), then it's not ever going to work.  In that case, I ask for your help in solving this problem on a raid by raid basis.  There *has* to be some way we can better work things out, than to send one raiding party packing because their schedule allowed for some other guild to get half an hour's jump on them.<P>I've tried to address the specifics of what happened between Triton and the Alliance Friday before last because I don't expect you to fix the attitudes of any other guilds - not directly, at least.  What you *can* do here, for the betterment of the server as a whole, is lead by example.  Make Triton's name one that everyone points to when they speak of the exceptions to "uberness."  The way I envision you doing that is, when you find out there's a raid planned for someplace you're going, at around the same time as your own raid, you make some effort to work out a compromise.  What happened the Friday before last wasn't a compromise, it was a steamroller - it was "We're going up because we don't think you're ready to go up, and it's our turn anyway, so bugger off."  There was no discussion - just someone in Triton making a conscious decision to ignore Eronmore and the Alliance raid, rather than advise your own raid leader of the situation and let the raid leaders work something out.<P>Cheers-<BR>Nalaureth sul'Fate<BR>GL, Hands of Faith (Povar)<BR>51 Ranger of Kelethin
